,"1324":"1324","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","1254":"1254","1330":"1330","about 1310":"about 1310","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Menteith, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Gleneagles, Perthshire, Scotland":"Gleneagles, Perthshire, Scotland","Clackmannanshire, Scotland":"Clackmannanshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Arnot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Arnott  .","German: variant of   Arnold  . This surname is very rare in Germany. In North America, it may also be an altered form of the variant <b>Arnodt</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Arnott","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place called Arnot in Portmoak, Kinross.","Scottish and English: variant of   Arnold  .","English: variant of   Arnett  ."]},{"name":"Jarnot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse.","Polish: from the personal name <i>Jarnot</i>, an adaptation of German   Arnot  . It occurs mainly in western part of Greater Poland and on the borderland of Silesia and Lesser Poland (the areas of old German settlement in Poland).","French: variant of   Garneau  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]},{"name":"Countess","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire, of Norman origin): from Middle English <i>contas(e)</i>, Old French <i>contesse</i> ‘countess’, applied as a nickname for a proud, haughty woman or for a foppish man, or as an occupational name for a servant of a countess."],"variants":[{"name":"Countiss","meanings":["English: variant of   Countess  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Matilda Countess de Arnot was born in 1254, in Gleneagles, Perthshire, Scotland. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Alexander 